    <stitle>MULTI-LINK FRONT AIR SUSPENSION - REMOVE AND INSTALL PROCEDURES - SWAY BAR</stitle>
    <svcsection/>
    <svcproc svcproctype="Remove and Install" graphiccount="3">
        <title>SWAY BAR</title>
        <svcsubproc>
            <title>Sway Bar - Removal</title>
            <figure id="g0301512" figsize="col-wide">
                <graphic filename="../figg03/g0301512.webp" type="webp" scalefitwidth="312px" scalefitheight="312px"/>
                <caption>Figure 13. Sway Bar Mounting</caption>
                <calloutgroup>
                    <callout1>1. LEFT LOWER TORQUE ROD</callout1>
                    <callout1>2. NUTS</callout1>
                    <callout1>3. RIGHT LOWER TORQUE ROD</callout1>
                    <callout1>4. SWAY BAR</callout1>
                    <callout1>5. SWAY BAR CLAMPS</callout1>
                    <callout1>6. BOLTS</callout1>
                </calloutgroup>
            </figure>
            <specpara>
                <note>
                    <para>It is recommended the vehicle be unloaded prior to performing this procedure. Vehicle must be
                        at approximate air spring height.
                    </para>
                </note>
            </specpara>
            <step1>
                <para count="1">Remove four nuts, bolts, and sway bar clamps from the left lower torque rod and sway
                    bar.
                </para>
            </step1>
            <step1>
                <para count="1">Remove four nuts, bolts, and sway bar clamps from the right lower torque rod and sway
                    bar.
                </para>
            </step1>
            <step1>
                <para count="1">Remove the sway bar.</para>
            </step1>
        </svcsubproc>
        <svcsubproc>
            <title>Sway Bar - Installation</title>
            <figure id="f0301528" figsize="col-wide">
                <graphic filename="../figg03/g0301528.webp" type="webp"/>
                <caption>Figure 14. Torque Rod Alignment Rib</caption>
                <calloutgroup>
                    <callout1>1. REAR WELD BEAD</callout1>
                    <callout1>2. REAR SWAY BAR CLAMPS</callout1>
                    <callout1>3. SWAY BAR</callout1>
                    <callout1>4. LOWER TORQUE ROD</callout1>
                    <callout1>5. MEGA BRACKET</callout1>
                </calloutgroup>
            </figure>
            <specpara>
                <caution>
                    <para>Failure to align the sway bar on the torque rod rear weld beads properly will allow the sway
                        bar to contact the mega brackets.
                    </para>
                </caution>
            </specpara>
            <step1>
                <para count="1">With the aid of an assistant, align the sway bar on the lower torque rods.</para>
            </step1>
            <step1>
                <para count="1">Install two rear sway bar clamps, bolts, and nuts on the left lower torque rod and sway
                    bar making sure to align the rear sway bar clamps on the rear weld bead. Do not tighten bolts at
                    this time.
                </para>
            </step1>
            <step1>
                <para count="1">Install two rear sway bar clamps, bolts, and nuts on the right lower torque rod and sway
                    bar making sure to align the rear sway bar clamps on the rear weld bead. Do not tighten bolts at
                    this time.
                </para>
            </step1>
            <step1>
                <para count="1">Install two remaining sway bar clamps, bolts, and nuts on the left lower torque rod and
                    sway bar (
                    <hotlnk xrefid="f0301512">Figure 14</hotlnk>). Do not tighten bolts at this time.
                </para>
            </step1>
            <step1>
                <para count="1">Install two remaining sway bar clamps, bolts, and nuts on the right lower torque rod and
                    sway bar (
                    <hotlnk xrefid="f0301512">Figure 14</hotlnk>). Do not tighten bolts at this time.
                </para>
            </step1>
            <figure id="f0301517" figsize="col-wide">
                <graphic filename="../figg03/g0301517.webp" type="webp" scalefitwidth="312px" scalefitheight="312px"/>
                <caption>Figure 15. Sway Bar Clamps</caption>
                <calloutgroup>
                    <callout1>1. BOTTOM BOLT</callout1>
                    <callout1>2. TOP BOLT</callout1>
                    <callout1>3. GAP BETWEEN SWAY BAR CLAMPS</callout1>
                    <callout1>4. SWAY BAR CLAMPS</callout1>
                </calloutgroup>
            </figure>
            <specpara>
                <note>
                    <para>When properly installed, a gap will be present along both the bottom and top of each sway bar
                        clamp.
                    </para>
                </note>
            </specpara>
            <step1>
                <para count="1">Follow these steps to secure the sway bar clamps:</para>
                <seqlist style="alphalc">
                    <item>
                        <para>Install two sway bar clamps on each side of sway bar and install two bolts and nuts on
                            each sway bar clamp.
                        </para>
                    </item>
                    <item>
                        <para>Tighten all bolts, making sure that a gap is shown at top and bottom of each sway bar
                            clamp.
                        </para>
                    </item>
                    <item>
                        <para>Torque each sway bar clamp by first torquing the bottom bolt and then the top. Torque
                            bolts to 80 to 100 lbf-ft (108 to 135 N&#8226;m).
                        </para>
                    </item>
                </seqlist>
            </step1>
        </svcsubproc>
    </svcproc>
